[Student "S"]
{You have 6 HCP and a 5-card suit. Although you can't be sure, there is a good chance your hand will be useful to partner.

So you bid 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \S4. You play dummy's \S3 and North contributes the \S6.

 You can get them in \Cs, but only if you are careful. 

After you unblock the \C A K you will go to dummy and play the \CJ. Then, after the \CQ is driven out you will return to dummy for the two \C winners. That means you need <b>TWO</b> dummy entries. 

Those two entries can only be the \SK and \SJ. So you absolutely <b>MUST</b> win the first trick in your hand with the \SA. Then play the \C A K. Over to dummy by playing \S9 to \SJ. Lead the \CJ to drive out the \CQ. Win whatever they return and play \SQ to \SK to reach your two good \Cs.

When you need dummy entries you may need to win a trick in your hand with an unnecessarily high card - like in this case.

You can only win 3 \S tricks however you play it, so you play to suit your entry needs.}
[Play "W"]S4

